		     ################################### 
		     # 				       # 
                     # Police Promise Led To Nightmare # 
		     # 				       # 
	     	     ################################### 
  

SIR  -  For  almost  three  years  our family  has  been  living  through  a nightmare.  In May 1994,  when my son Richard was 16 years old,  there was a police  raid  on  our house.  A large number of officers removed  everything from Richard's bedroom while he huddled in shock in a corner.  This was  not a  raid for drugs or stolen property;  we were informed that he was "meeting undesirable characters over the Internet".  

We  were  not used to dealing with the police,  and believed them when  they said  that there was nothing to worry about,  and this would not affect  his future.  Three years later,  we have been through endless delays  and  court appearances and nobody seems to be able to resolve the situation.  

Richard  is  a  very  talented  double bass  player  who  last  year  won  a scholarship to the Royal College of Music.  I do not know how he is managing to  concentrate  on his studies.  It was not until 12 days  after  his  18th birthday  that  he was charged with unauthorised access to various  computer systems in the United States.  

This  meant  that  his  name could be released,  and  the  inevitable  press interest  began.  Since then,  the police and the Crown Prosecution  Service have spent vast sums of public money on this case,  including travelling  to the  United States on at least two occasions,  for several weeks each  time, trying to make out a case against him.  

Last year there was a report in the United States on the 250,000 attempts  a year  from  people to access the computers at the Pentagon.   Shortly  after that  report,  and more than two years after his arrest,  the  charges  were changed to "conspiracy",  and he had to face going to Crown Court instead of magistrates' court.  More delays followed.  On March 14,  those charges were rescinded.  

With  all  the rather nasty computer crimes that happen nowadays,  I  cannot understand  why  we  have been in the middle of this  ludicrous  and  almost surreal situation.  Richard will have a wonderful future in music,  if he is allowed.  

I  understand  that computer "hacking" has to be stopped.   But  surely  the United  States administration cannot believe that it will get good publicity from  insisting on this prosecution,  using Richard as an example to others. If  it  is  possible for a 16 year old,  with very ordinary  equipment,   to access their American system from his bedroom,  surely the fault lies in the system?  

Perhaps they should have asked where the fault lay,  rather than ruining  my son's life.  

(Mrs) ALISON PRYCE 
London NW9 
